  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mobilising Action to Safeguard Rights of Girls in Tanzania</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Female genital mutilation (FGM), child marriage and early pregnancies lead to health and other problems for girls in Tanzania. Girls are taken out of primary school and, as child brides, often experience high rates of domestic violence. As young widows, or divorced, their plight worsens, and they lose their property rights, as they struggle to care for their children when still children themselves. The voices, views and experiences of some of these young women have been movingly captured in a recent piece of action research. The girls have formed a self-help network, and with a little support have begun to find their confidence, had training, counselling and legal advice on their rights, and have started catering and sewing small businesses. Now, along with the local organisations that have been supporting them, they want to help form new networks so others like them can be helped.  The project will also prevent future abuse through schools-based clubs for younger girl children which will let them know of the dangers of FGM and child marriage, make them aware of their rights and how to exercise them to prevent abuse. Advocacy with government officials, communities and parents will spread the beneficial results more widely.</narrative>
  </description>
